{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:32:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:32:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"829"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/829"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.12,0.16,0.53,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67934"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/829"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53399"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"526"},{"type":"tags","id":"904"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44485"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67934"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to Emergency Department after developing abdominal distension one week after a left total arthroplasty for a neck of femur fracture, sustained after falling from a ladder.\u00a0On review, he describes two days of diarrhoea and rapidly progressive abdominal distension, with a 12 hour history of nausea and vomiting. He has mild dull, constant abdominal pain and some mild tenderness in his left flank region. Apart from his recent hospitalisation, his only significant medical history is hypertension. On examination his blood pressure is 135/92 mmHg, pulse 94/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His abdomen is obviously distended (Image). It is tympanic and mildly tender with decreased bowel sounds on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Small bowel obstruction","Large bowel  obstruction","Clostridioides difficile infection","Pseudo-obstruction","Sigmoid volvulus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this patient. Most commonly presenting after surgery (particularly orthopaedic) and/or administration of medications that inhibit colonic motility (e.g. opioids or anticholinergics), it is a functional obstruction of intestinal contents without an anatomical lesion causing the obstruction. The patients may have either constipation or diarrhoea. Presenting similarly to a mechanical bowel obstruction, it is differentiated predominantly by painless rapid abdominal distension with reduced, but not absent, bowel sounds. An abdominal CT is the gold standard for diagnosing this condition through colonic dilatation with a lack of distinct radiographical evidence for an anatomical lesion or an abrupt transition point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge bowel mechanical obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall bowel mechanical obstruction \u003C/strong\u003Ewould result in a similar clinical presentation and therefore have to be considered as diagnostic possibilities. However, a mechanical bowel obstruction is more likely to present with colicky abdominal pain, tender abdomen and absolute constipation - none of which this patient has. Colicky abdominal pain is due to peristalsis of the bowel surrounding an anatomical obstruction, something which is not present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/strong\u003E is a common infection in hospital patients, it usually presents with diarrhoea, cramping abdominal pain, abdominal tenderness and fever. Given this patient has neither cramping abdominal and fever, along with only mild abdominal tenderness, this is not the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E is a strong potential diagnosis for this scenario. Presenting similarly to a mechanical bowel obstruction, in the case of a volvulus there is a twisiting of the colon. Often occuring in bed-bound post-surgical patients, a sigmoid volvulus is the most common type of volvulus (others include caecal and transverse colon). It can lead to severe complications if untreated, such as ischaemia and perforation. Diagnosis can be made using a plain abdominal X-ray or CT. In this case however, it usually presents with more abdominal pain and absolute constipation, neither of which this patient has.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT is the gold-standard modality from which to diagnose pseudo-obstruction"],"references":["Camilleri, M. Acute colonic pseudo-obstruction (Ogilvie\u0027s syndrome). In: UpToDate, Post TW (Ed), UpToDate, Waltham, MA. (Accessed on February 17, 2023.)","Singh, G., El-Feky, M., Hacking, C., et al. Colonic pseudo-obstruction. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 17 Feb 2023)","Yeh, M. D., Bordeianou, L. Large bowel obstruction. In: UpToDate, Post TW (Ed), UpToDate, Waltham, MA. (Accessed on February 17, 2023.)","Lamont, J. T., Kelly, C. P., Bakken, J. S. Clostridioides difficile infection in adults: Clinical manifestations and diagnosis. In: UpToDate, Post TW (Ed), UpToDate, Waltham, MA. (Accessed on February 17, 2023.)","Lieske, B., \u0026 Antunes, C. (2022). Sigmoid Volvulus. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441925/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53399"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"829"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19245"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19245"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c6e88670-2f41-473e-9a1c-0a6ad751770c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c6e88670-2f41-473e-9a1c-0a6ad751770c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53399"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T23:29:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T23:29:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"829"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67934"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"des